<TITLE> Eid celebrated around the world </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Muslims around the world are celebrating Eid-ul-Azha or Festival of Sacrifice - a four-day holiday marking the end of the hajj pilgrimage. Islam marks its second largest festival with prayers and sacrifice. In Bangladesh, thousands upon thousands of people scrambled to get out of the capital of Dhaka and head to the provinces. A rush of commuters clogged the city's streets, ferries were full to bursting and trains crammed full. The festival of sacrifice represents Abraham's obedience to God and willingness to offer his own son. Families slaughter animals and donate the cuts to the needy. For some its an annual treat as they're normally too poor to eat meat. In the Gaza strip, which remains under Israeli blockade, the faithful prayed alongside Hamas leader Ismail Haniyeh. In Indonesia, after prayers many head to cemeteries to visit lost loved ones in another typical Eid tradition. And in Jerusalem's Old City, thousands came to the al-Aqsa mosque -- the second oldest in I
